<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<topic id="e0846733-419c-11e1-9d4f-002421116fb2" revisionNumber="1">
	<developerHowToDocument
	  xmlns="http://ddue.schemas.microsoft.com/authoring/2003/5"
	  xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">

		<introduction>
			<para>
				You can use the Double Agent <token>ActiveXCtl</token> in any programming environment that supports
				the <token>COM</token> standard or the <token>dotNET</token>
				standard. This includes <token>VB</token> 6, <token>VB</token> .NET, Visual C#, Visual C++,
				JScript, VBScript, and many other programming languages.
			</para>
		</introduction>
		<section>
			<content>
				<para>
					For programming languages that support native <token>Windows</token> programming, use Double Agent's
					native <token>ActiveXCtl</token>.
				</para>
				<list class="bullet">
					<listItem>
						<para>
							To include the control in a form, make sure the language fully supports the <token>ActiveXInt</token>
							and follow its conventions for adding and accessing <token>ActiveXCtls</token>.
						</para>
					</listItem>
					<listItem>
						<para>
							If the language supports it, you can also use the <languageKeyword>New</languageKeyword> operator
							with the &quot;DoubleAgent.Control&quot; or &quot;DoubleAgent.Control.1.1&quot;
							<languageKeyword>ProgID</languageKeyword>, or the &quot;{1147E530-A208-11DE-ABF2-002421116FB2}&quot;
							<languageKeyword>ClassID</languageKeyword>.
						</para>
					</listItem>
				</list>
				<para>
					The programming environment may require a declared reference to the control's <token>COM</token> type library:
				</para>
				<list class="bullet">
					<listItem>
						<para>
							The native control is registered as an <token>ActiveXCtl</token> object.
							If the programming environment provides a list of registered
							<token>ActiveXCtl</token> or <token>COMauto</token>
							objects, it will appear in the list.
						</para>
					</listItem>
					<listItem>
						<para>
							A <legacyItalic>reference copy</legacyItalic> of the control's <token>COM</token> type library
							is installed with the <link xlink:href="e0846731-419c-11e1-9d4f-002421116fb2#DevFiles">Double Agent SDK</link>
							in folder <localUri>C:\Program&#160;Files\Double&#160;Agent\Dev</localUri>.
						</para>
					</listItem>
					<listItem>
						<para>
							For programming environments that prefer to retrieve type information from the actual
							run-time, a <legacyItalic>copy</legacyItalic> of the control's <token>COM</token> type library
							is also included in the control's run-time (<localUri>DaControl.dll</localUri>)
							as an embedded resource.
						</para>
					</listItem>
				</list>
			</content>
		</section>
		<section>
			<content>
				<para>
					For programming languages that support the <token>dotNET</token>&#160;<legacyItalic>Common Language Runtime (CLR)</legacyItalic>, there are two options:
				</para>
				<list class="ordered">
					<listItem>
						<para>
							You can use Double Agent's Control <token>PIA</token>.
						</para>
						<list class="bullet">
							<listItem>
								<para>
									It provides the Double Agent Control as simple a <token>dotNET</token>
									object (a subclass of <unmanagedCodeEntityReference>System.Object</unmanagedCodeEntityReference>)
									that you can instantiate using the
									<languageKeyword>New</languageKeyword> operator (no form required).
								</para>
							</listItem>
							<listItem>
								<para>
									Use the <codeEntityReference qualifyHint="false">T:DoubleAgent.Control.Control</codeEntityReference> class in
									the <codeEntityReference qualifyHint="true">N:DoubleAgent.Control</codeEntityReference>
									namespace.

								</para>
							</listItem>
						</list>
					</listItem>
					<listItem>
						<para>
							If the language supports the <unmanagedCodeEntityReference>System.Windows.Forms</unmanagedCodeEntityReference> namespace,
							you can use Double Agent's <token>ActiveXCtl</token>&#160;<token>PIA</token>.
						</para>
						<list class="bullet">
							<listItem>
								<para>
									It provides the Double Agent Control as a <token>WinFormsCtl</token>
									(a subclass of <unmanagedCodeEntityReference>System.Windows.Forms.Control</unmanagedCodeEntityReference>) that you can
									drop in any form.
								</para>
							</listItem>
							<listItem>
								<para>
									Use the <codeEntityReference qualifyHint="false">T:DoubleAgent.Control.AxControl</codeEntityReference> class
									in the <codeEntityReference qualifyHint="true">N:DoubleAgent.AxControl</codeEntityReference>
									namespace.
								</para>
							</listItem>
						</list>
					</listItem>
				</list>
				<para>
					The programming environment may require a declared reference to these assemblies:
				</para>
				<list class="bullet">
					<listItem>
						<para>
							For a programming environment that retrieves references from the
							<token>GACname</token> (<token>GAC</token>), these assemblies are added to the <token>GAC</token>
							when Double Agent is installed.
						</para>
						<para>
							There are different versions of the <token>PIAs</token>
							for <token>dotNET</token> 3.5 or earlier and <token>dotNET</token>
							4.0 or later. If you move from <token>dotNET</token> 3.5 to
							<token>dotNET</token> 4.0 you should reinstall the
							<link xlink:href="e0846731-419c-11e1-9d4f-002421116fb2#DevFiles">Double Agent SDK</link>
							to get the correct <token>PIA</token>
							versions installed in the the <token>GAC</token>.
						</para>
					</listItem>
					<listItem>
						<para>
							If an assembly file is required, a <legacyItalic>reference copy</legacyItalic> of these assemblies is
							installed with the <link xlink:href="e0846731-419c-11e1-9d4f-002421116fb2#DevFiles">Double Agent SDK</link>
							in folder <localUri>C:\Program&#160;Files\Double&#160;Agent\Dev\v3.5</localUri> (for
							<token>dotNET</token> 3.5 or earlier) or <localUri>C:\Program&#160;Files\Double&#160;Agent\Dev\v4.0</localUri>
							(for <token>dotNET</token> 4.0 or later).
						</para>
					</listItem>
					<listItem>
						<para>
							You can use a reference to a specific assembly's full path, or add the SDK install
							location to the programming environment's reference search path.
						</para>
					</listItem>
				</list>
			</content>
		</section>

